00:48:56.940 --> 00:48:58.356
that I know that's
here at Google.

00:48:58.356 --> 00:48:59.970
And I think I'm
really excited to see

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:02.610
what it does in the industry
of Toronto and Canada

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:03.575
and opera in this area.

00:49:03.575 --> 00:49:05.700
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT: Well, I
mean, just to sort of try

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:07.690
and mend this gap over
here a little bit--

00:49:07.690 --> 00:49:08.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:08.190 --> 00:49:09.064
BOB CORNWALL: Please.

00:49:09.064 --> 00:49:12.570
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT: I would say,
though, that opera in Canada

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:17.040
actually has a very
distinguished history.

00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:20.740
Some of the greatest opera
singers that ever lived

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:22.830
were Canadian.

00:49:22.830 --> 00:49:26.730
Back to Albani, right?

00:49:26.730 --> 00:49:27.230
Alba--

00:49:27.230 --> 00:49:28.230
CORI ELLISON: Emma Albani?

00:49:28.230 --> 00:49:29.360
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT:
Emma Albani, who was--

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:31.610
CORI ELLISON: You had Edward
Johnson, who ran the Met.

00:49:31.610 --> 00:49:36.420
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT: And
arguably, from Toronto proper,

00:49:36.420 --> 00:49:39.650
one of the greatest
singing actresses

00:49:39.650 --> 00:49:43.620
is Teresa Stratus,
who I grew up with,

00:49:43.620 --> 00:49:46.140
watching her do "La Traviata"
and stuff like that,

00:49:46.140 --> 00:49:48.450
and "Dialogue of
the Carmelites."

00:49:48.450 --> 00:49:49.950
And then when you
go to Jon Vickers,

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:52.020
and Maureen Forrester,
and people like that.

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:56.610
I do feel that in Canada,
there has been a kind of--

00:49:56.610 --> 00:49:58.920
how can I say--

00:49:58.920 --> 00:50:13.950
more of attention paid to the
holistic of being an artist.

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:18.260
And it has translated well
in opera here particularly.

00:50:18.260 --> 00:50:23.780
I mean, because you don't have
some somewhere like the Met,

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:26.330
or somewhere like La Scala where
they just kind of like shoot

00:50:26.330 --> 00:50:28.690
them out and it's
more of a machine,

00:50:28.690 --> 00:50:32.990
here, I think opera is and
has been for many years,

00:50:32.990 --> 00:50:33.920
really prized.

00:50:33.920 --> 00:50:36.620
Because we're aware
of how special

00:50:36.620 --> 00:50:39.441
it is because it's not
taken for granted as much.

00:50:39.441 --> 00:50:40.440
BOB CORNWALL: Thank you.

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:40.890
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT: So that's--

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:42.640
DANIEL MACIVOR: Holistic,
that's the word.

00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:43.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:44.236
More holistic.

00:50:44.236 --> 00:50:46.110
BOB CORNWALL: That's
what you're looking for.

00:50:46.110 --> 00:50:47.094
Last audience question.

00:50:47.094 --> 00:50:49.010
AUDIENCE: Yes, I wanted
to go back to the idea

00:50:49.010 --> 00:50:52.670
that you brought up,
Isaiah, this idea of history

00:50:52.670 --> 00:50:54.770
and going back into history.

00:50:54.770 --> 00:50:58.730
We're here in a new city in
a new country with an opera

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:00.980
company that is quite new
in the big scheme of things.

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:05.820
Rufus, you work primarily in
a relatively new art form.

00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:08.240
But here with opera,
you're taking an art form

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:10.580
that has centuries
of history that

00:51:10.580 --> 00:51:12.260
has changed, of
course, over time,

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:14.990
from a more popular art form to
something that's somewhat more

00:51:14.990 --> 00:51:17.020
rarefied air these days.

00:51:17.020 --> 00:51:20.120
And you're looking at a story
set in Roman times, which

00:51:20.120 --> 00:51:23.517
goes back millennia now.

00:51:23.517 --> 00:51:25.100
Can you talk a little
bit about if you

00:51:25.100 --> 00:51:28.820
feel any burden of taking
on this mantle of history,

00:51:28.820 --> 00:51:33.100
in both the art form and the
story that you're telling?

00:51:33.100 --> 00:51:35.100
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT: Yeah.

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:36.360
I mean, there's one--

00:51:36.360 --> 00:51:38.760
it's funny, there hasn't
been much talk about it.

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:48.840
And perhaps my
safe side should be

00:51:48.840 --> 00:51:54.220
more on par with the idea of
just not talking about it.

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:59.160
But my Rufus side feels like,
let's just talk about it.

00:51:59.160 --> 00:52:01.830
I mean, there is very dark
sides of this opera, which

00:52:01.830 --> 00:52:05.970
is that Hadrian was responsible
for the first really

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:07.290
big Jewish massacre.

00:52:07.290 --> 00:52:09.050
And it's addressed in the piece.

00:52:09.050 --> 00:52:13.290
And he basically
created Palestine.

00:52:13.290 --> 00:52:16.770
He kicked the Jews out of Judea.

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:21.480
So this is a situation that
we're very much dealing

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.220
with still to this very day.

00:52:26.760 --> 00:52:31.180
And in our piece, we address
that, and we work with that.

00:52:31.180 --> 00:52:38.520
And so certainly,
embarking on this

00:52:38.520 --> 00:52:41.910
with that question
in mind, I was

00:52:41.910 --> 00:52:49.350
very worried about how it
would be read, and I still am.

00:52:49.350 --> 00:52:52.440
But that being said,
I do feel that--

00:52:52.440 --> 00:52:55.680
and I know that Daniel's
totally on board with me here--

00:52:55.680 --> 00:53:03.210
is that what we are trying
to put forth is that it's not

00:53:03.210 --> 00:53:03.910
so much--

00:53:03.910 --> 00:53:07.350
I mean, because within our
opera, we talk about the Jews,

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:08.950
but we also talk
about the Nazarenes,

00:53:08.950 --> 00:53:10.440
so the early Christians.

00:53:10.440 --> 00:53:13.710
And it's really this whole
concept of monotheism

00:53:13.710 --> 00:53:17.010
that is about to
eclipse the pagan world,

00:53:17.010 --> 00:53:24.660
and how that, even to this
day, me personally, I feel

00:53:24.660 --> 00:53:26.515
was not the best move.

00:53:26.515 --> 00:53:27.305
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:27.305 --> 00:53:29.055
DANIEL MACIVOR:
On that we agree.

00:53:29.055 --> 00:53:30.680
RUFUS WAINWRIGHT:
And I'm happy and I'm

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:36.060
happy to stand
behind that theory.

00:53:36.060 --> 00:53:39.680
So I don't agree
with the massacre.

00:53:39.680 --> 00:53:41.060
I'm not condoning anything.

00:53:41.060 --> 00:53:46.740
But I do feel that just on a
personal level, that later on,

00:53:46.740 --> 00:53:50.700
when Constantine became
Christian and then turned

00:53:50.700 --> 00:53:55.110
the entire empire into
a Christian empire,

00:53:55.110 --> 00:54:00.390
for me, that was not a great
day in history, frankly.

00:54:00.390 --> 00:54:02.550
And that's an argument
that I'm willing to have.

00:54:02.550 --> 00:54:08.040
And I think that this opera kind
of presents that conversation,

00:54:08.040 --> 00:54:11.340
which I think is a
conversation that we're

00:54:11.340 --> 00:54:14.145
very much engaged in right now.

00:54:14.145 --> 00:54:16.950
PETER HINTON: And I do think
it's important to state

00:54:16.950 --> 00:54:24.630
that this identification of
Canada as a young country is

00:54:24.630 --> 00:54:29.190
really, really dubious,
given the many nations

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:34.440
and cultures upon which
Canada was forged, claimed,

00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:38.430
and colonized, civilizations
that have been here

00:54:38.430 --> 00:54:40.450
for 10,000 years.

00:54:40.450 --> 00:54:46.740
So we have our own empire
drama that we're living now.

00:54:46.740 --> 00:54:51.680
And I think it's very resonant
to Canadians in that regard.

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:54.240
BOB CORNWALL: Yeah, thank you.

00:54:54.240 --> 00:54:55.080
It's fascinating.

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:56.996
I think it's a really
interesting conversation

00:54:56.996 --> 00:54:58.070
and debate.

00:54:58.070 --> 00:55:00.840
And you see that riddled
within the play, which I think

00:55:00.840 --> 00:55:01.770
is fantastic.

